    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Is there a variable in the Cython API I could use to determine if I'm running of 32-bits? (or 64)\r\n\r\nsomething that would look somewhat like this:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nfrom cython.foo.bar.baz import is_32_bits\r\n```\r\n\r\nThat would be a ```bint``` (or with other type and value), so it could later be used in ```if/else``` statements.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nWhat I am trying to ask is, what is the encouraged way to check if the running platform is 32-bits, inside a ```cython``` file?",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "You could do the following - check the size of the pointer type:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nfrom libc.stdint cimport intptr_t\r\n\r\nif sizeof(intptr_t) == 4:\r\n```\r\n\r\nBut it seems like a good idea for Cython to provide stuff like this as compile-time constants for `IF/ELIF/ELSE`.\r\n",
